{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582791"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:55:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:55:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"870"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/870"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.81,0.06,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"870"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101624"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/870"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"870"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84065"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"380"},{"type":"tags","id":"1216"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"9385"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35225"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101624"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of intermittent pain and paraesthesia in her right hand. The symptoms are worse at night and often wake her from sleep. She reports relief by shaking or massaging her hand. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. Her medications include metformin, gliclazide, and amlodipine. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her right hand is inspected (Image). \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying pathophysiological mechanism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Demyelination of the ulnar nerve","Compression of the median nerve at the carpal tunnel","Cervical radiculopathy affecting C6-C7","Thoracic outlet syndrome","Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is of carpal tunnel syndrome, caused by \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompression of the median nerve at the carpal tunnel\u003C/strong\u003E. This compression can lead to demyelination and axonal loss in the nerve, resulting in the characteristic symptoms of pain and paraesthesia in the thumb, index, middle, and radial aspect of the ring finger. The photo provided shows thenar muscle wasting, which occurs as the thenar muscles are innervated by the median nerve. The abductor pollicis brevis muscle, which is part of the thenar eminence, is often the first to show wasting in carpal tunnel syndrome due to its exclusive median nerve innervation. This sign and the patient\u0027s nocturnal pain and paraesthesia with relief by shaking further supports the diagnosis. It\u0027s worth noting that carpal tunnel syndrome is more common in patients with diabetes, as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDemyelination of the ulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E would typically cause symptoms in the medial aspect of the hand and the fourth and fifth digits, which is not the case here. Ulnar nerve entrapment usually presents with weakness of the intrinsic hand muscles and sensory changes in the fifth digit and medial half of the fourth digit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical radiculopathy affecting C6-C7\u003C/strong\u003E could cause pain and sensory changes in the hand, but would typically also involve the forearm and possibly the upper arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThoracic outlet syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can cause pain and paraesthesia in the arm and hand, but typically affects the entire hand and arm, often worsening with arm elevation. It would not explain the specific median nerve distribution of symptoms or the thenar muscle wasting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERaynaud\u0027s phenomenon\u003C/strong\u003E causes episodic colour changes and pain in the fingers in response to cold or stress. It typically affects all fingers symmetrically and would not explain the thenar muscle wasting or symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Median nerve entrapment can result in wasting of the thenar eminence, particularly the abductor pollicis brevis muscle.","Median nerve entrapment can result in paraesthesia affecting the lateral palm and lateral three and a half digits.","Carpal tunnel syndrome is more common with conditions such as diabetes, hypothyroidism, and pregnancy."],"references":["Pryse-Phillips WE. Validation of a diagnostic sign in carpal tunnel syndrome. J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry. 1984 Aug;47(8):870-2. doi: 10.1136/jnnp.47.8.870. PMID: 6470728; PMCID: PMC1027954. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1027954/","Fuchs HA. Joint counts and physical measures. Rheum Dis Clin North Am. 1995 May;21(2):429-44. PMID: 7631037. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7631037/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84065"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"870"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16324"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16324"},"attributes":{"mime